docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON, June 6. -- Foreign trade in April increased with every geographical grand division compared with April, 1935, the Department of Commerce announced today. Exports totaled $192,692,000, compared with $164,151,000 a year ago. Imports amounted to $202,789,000, compared with $170,500,000.

docs.lead_paragraph: The emergency fund American seamen's welfare age benefited to the extent of $3,222.80 because of the visit of the new Cunard White Star liner Queen Mary to this port. Kermit Roosevelt, treasurer of the fund, in his weekly report yesterday, said $8,154 had been collected from visitors to the new liner, and expenses were $38.80, leaving $8,115.20.

docs.lead_paragraph: Foreign exchanges milled about last week very much in the fashion which marked other periods. Business was never unusually active, but it was evident that a nervous undertone persisted with respect to the future of the French franc which brought in its wake fresh engagements of gold in Paris for this country.
